{"parse":{"title":"Ragamuffin parade","pageid":52795561,"revid":849045130,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg/220px-2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"293\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg/330px-2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg/440px-2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2448\" data-file-height=\"3264\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:2013_Ragamuffin_parade.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Part of <a href=\"/wiki/Bay_Ridge\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bay Ridge\">Bay Ridge</a>'s 2013 Ragamuffin Parade</div></div></div>\n<p>A <b>Ragamuffin parade</b> is an annual occurrence in communities in the <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_metropolitan_area\" title=\"New York metropolitan area\">New York metropolitan area</a>. The parades feature children in their <a href=\"/wiki/Halloween\" title=\"Halloween\">Halloween</a> costumes, and typically are held in October or on Halloween. The holiday formed around 1870, a few years after US President Abraham Lincoln declared <a href=\"/wiki/Thanksgiving\" title=\"Thanksgiving\">Thanksgiving</a> a national holiday.\n</p><p>It had its origins with Ragamuffin Day, a celebration as part of Thanksgiving, which involved children going door-to-door seeking candy, dressed as beggars and homeless residents of New York. Ragamuffin Day was a predecessor to Halloween, which rose in popularity in the 1940s and 1950s.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYPL_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYPL-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Ragamuffin_Day\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Ragamuffin Day</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Present_day\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Present day</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ragamuffin_parade&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Ragamuffin_Day\">Ragamuffin Day</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ragamuffin_parade&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Ragamuffin Day\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Ragamuffin Day formed around 1870, a few years after US President Abraham Lincoln declared Thanksgiving a national holiday. Ragamuffin Day took place on Thanksgiving, and typically involved children going from door to door asking for candy or money. These children were originally dressed in the style of the homeless of New York,<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> with rags and oversized and exaggerated imitations of beggars.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYPL_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYPL-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In further years, the children dressed as sailors, bandits and Disney characters. In the 1930s, the begging tradition was superseded by Ragamuffin parades, a predecessor of Thanksgiving Day parades. As Halloween became popular after the Great Depression, Ragamuffin events became less popular, however children continued the traditions into the 1940s.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Around 1930, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_New_York_Times\" title=\"The New York Times\">The New York Times</a></i> published several articles in an attempt to end the tradition, that the children would \"annoy adults\" on Thanksgiving Day with their pleas for candy, money, and gifts. Later that year the newspaper reported that the parades were scarce in New York City, except in its outskirts, where the subway lines end.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYPL_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYPL-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>By 1937 several organizations began hosting Thanksgiving Day parades to discourage Ragamuffins, where the Thanksgiving parades would also feature children dressed both as beggars and in Halloween costumes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYPL_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYPL-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In the 1940s, some of these parades involved around 500 children.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT1947_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT1947-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The last recorded Thanksgiving Day Ragamuffin parade was in 1956, overshadowed by <a href=\"/wiki/Macy%27s_Thanksgiving_Day_Parade\" title=\"Macy&#39;s Thanksgiving Day Parade\">Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYPL_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYPL-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> A Ragamuffin parade on October 15, 1972 in <a href=\"/wiki/Bay_Ridge,_Brooklyn\" title=\"Bay Ridge, Brooklyn\">Bay Ridge, Brooklyn</a>, brought about 6,000 children and a crowd of around 35,000, making it the largest Ragamuffin parade in the United States at that time.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT1972_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT1972-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Present_day\">Present day</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ragamuffin_parade&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Present day\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Ragamuffin parades continued in the outer boroughs of New York City after losing popularity in Manhattan. The parades are still held in the area, including in Bay Ridge, held since 1966, <a href=\"/wiki/Park_Ridge,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Park Ridge, New Jersey\">Park Ridge, New Jersey</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-PR_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PR-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> and in <a href=\"/wiki/Hoboken,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Hoboken, New Jersey\">Hoboken, New Jersey</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Other communities include the <a href=\"/wiki/Westchester_County\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Westchester County\">Westchester County</a> municipalities <a href=\"/wiki/Pleasantville,_New_York\" title=\"Pleasantville, New York\">Pleasantville</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Briarcliff_Manor\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Briarcliff Manor\">Briarcliff Manor</a> (where the parade has been held for about 30 years).<sup id=\"cite_ref-Pleasatville_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Pleasatville-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Briarcliff_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Briarcliff-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In September 2016, a street in Bay Ridge was renamed \"Ragamuffin Way\" in honor of the neighborhood's 50-year-old tradition.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Katinas_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Katinas-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Spivack_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Spivack-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ragamuffin_parade&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role=\"navigation\" aria-label=\"Portals\" class=\"noprint portal plainlist tright\" style=\"margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 1em;border:solid #aaa 1px\">\n<ul style=\"display:table;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0.1em;max-width:175px;background:#f9f9f9;font-size:85%;line-height:110%;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold\">\n<li style=\"display:table-row\"><span style=\"display:table-cell;padding:0.2em;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Calendar_icon.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Calendar_icon.svg/22px-Calendar_icon.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"28\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Calendar_icon.svg/33px-Calendar_icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Calendar_icon.svg/44px-Calendar_icon.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"720\" data-file-height=\"920\" /></a></span><span style=\"display:table-cell;padding:0.2em 0.2em 0.2em 0.3em;vertical-align:middle\"><a href=\"/wiki/Portal:Holidays\" title=\"Portal:Holidays\">Holidays portal</